   "source": [
    "## Functions \n",
    "subroutines are defined using ```def```"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def test(a,b=1,c=3,d=1):\n",
    "    return a*b*c\n",
    "\n",
    "test(1,b=3)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "## Argument passing\n",
    "* Python represents all its data as objects. \n",
    "* Variables are just names. \n",
    "* Some objects are mutable, some immutable.\n",
    " * Immutables are: int, float, complex, str, tuples, bytes, frozensets Mutables are: list, byte array, sets, dict, classes\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "With ```id``` is possible to check the unique identity of an object"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "n = 1 # integer immutable\n",
    "id(n)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "n += 1\n",
    "id(n) # new object"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "m = [1] #list mutable\n",
    "id(m)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "metadata": {
    "collapsed": false
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "m.append(2)\n",
    "id(m) #same object"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {
    "slideshow": {
     "slide_type": "slide"
    }
   },
   "source": [
    "## Argument passing\n",
    "* Passing an argument to a function is like creating a new name to the object, if it is mutable then any change inside the function will affect the object outside. \n",
    "* If it is immutable and the function changes it, then python creates another object inside the function scope, so nothing changes outside of the function."
   ]
  },
